  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_154789154" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/154789154" />
    <a title="Elizabeth (Alaska)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2026178-elizabeth-alaska"><img alt="Elizabeth (Alaska)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1304966095p2/2026178.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/154789154?book_show_action=true">Jul 02, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elizabeth (Alaska)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elizabeth (Alaska)" href="/user/show/2026178-elizabeth-alaska">Elizabeth (Alaska)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780394442297" href="/book/show/1026696.The_Reivers">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2026178-elizabeth-alaska?shelf=author-faulkner">author-faulkner</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2026178-elizabeth-alaska?shelf=awards-pulitzer">awards-pulitzer</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2026178-elizabeth-alaska?shelf=5-star-reads">5-star-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2026178-elizabeth-alaska?shelf=mid-20th-century">mid-20th-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2026178-elizabeth-alaska?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer154789154" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14038939793625476817">This has the subtitle &quot;A Reminiscence&quot; and, as Faulkner&apos;s last novel, when I saw that I thought perhaps it was somewhat autobiographical. Then, the opening line: <blockquote>Grandfather Said: This is the kind of a man Boon Hogganbeck was. Hung on the wall, it could have been his epitaph, like a Bertillon chart or a police poster; any cop in north Mississippi would have arrested him out of any crowd after merely reading the date.</blockquote>So, instead it is the reminiscence of a man who is now a grandfather, (probably </span>
  <span id="freeText14038939793625476817" style="display:none">This has the subtitle "A Reminiscence" and, as Faulkner's last novel, when I saw that I thought perhaps it was somewhat autobiographical. Then, the opening line: <blockquote>Grandfather Said: This is the kind of a man Boon Hogganbeck was. Hung on the wall, it could have been his epitaph, like a Bertillon chart or a police poster; any cop in north Mississippi would have arrested him out of any crowd after merely reading the date.</blockquote>So, instead it is the reminiscence of a man who is now a grandfather, (probably telling his grandson) of events in 1905 when he was eleven years old. The description of this being a comic novel is accurate. Faulkner also spent some time as a screenwriter and I could see such a movie, even though I've never seen the film. I just went to look and see that one of my very favorite actors, Steven McQueen, played Boon. He was cast perfectly, I think. <br /><br />In my mind's eye, I could see Faulkner writing this. He became the grandfather telling this story. He lived it as it filled the page. And so, too, did I live the story as I read. The trip to Memphis is eventful. And who takes an 11-year old boy to a whorehouse? But it is even better than that. I have a pretty good vocabulary, but somehow I missed the meaning of the title, which I found on the back flap of my copy: <em>reive (reave) take away by stealth or force; plunder.</em> It isn't just Boon and Lucius on this trip, but also Ned, a negro employee of Lucius' own grandfather, has stowed away. Ned was my favorite character. Boon saw the opportunity to "use" the car for 4 days while Lucius' parents and grandparents were away, but it was Ned who would plot to take full advantage of that opportunity. <br /><br />Before I finished this, I spent a bit of time here on GR making sure that I had all of Faulkner's fiction on any of my wishlists, noting whether I needed to buy them in digital format, or whether they are available from my library. I have enjoyed my time spent with other Faulkner titles, but this finally convinced me I would like to read everything. Yes, some of his novels are challenging, and few of them are comic. But he's just too good to pass up.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14038939793625476817" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


