  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/125723897" />
    <a title="Erik" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/795024-erik"><img alt="Erik" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1530815346p2/795024.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/125723897?book_show_action=true">Oct 11, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Erik" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Erik" href="/user/show/795024-erik">Erik</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780394442297" href="/book/show/1026696.The_Reivers">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/795024-erik?shelf=did-not-finish">did-not-finish</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer125723897" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11292440754327563070">The first 50+ pages was like listening to someone tell a story with so many tangents and sentences so long that I forget where it was even headed to being with. I understand the style was part of the story, but I don&apos;t like hearing a story told in that manner in real life, so it lost its novelty quickly. I laughed out loud once, but the rest of the humor never even got a smile. The only reason I can see this won a Pulitzer is because of the year it was published and the racial commentary (not a </span>
  <span id="freeText11292440754327563070" style="display:none">The first 50+ pages was like listening to someone tell a story with so many tangents and sentences so long that I forget where it was even headed to being with. I understand the style was part of the story, but I don't like hearing a story told in that manner in real life, so it lost its novelty quickly. I laughed out loud once, but the rest of the humor never even got a smile. The only reason I can see this won a Pulitzer is because of the year it was published and the racial commentary (not a main theme, but prevalent). If the same book were published now (by an unknown), I don't think it would garner so much as a nod. I started skimming with 50 pages to go, not really caring much about the outcome. This book is definitely not for me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11292440754327563070" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


