        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer878357978" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16249680063117388504">I had some trouble to fight my way through this novel.<br/><br/>The story is actually quite interesting and amusing: The three heroes, 11 yo Lucius, Boon Hogganbeck and &quot;Uncle&quot; Ned pilfer the car of Lucius&apos; grandfather and want to travel for four days to the &quot;big city&quot;. You have to understand that at the time in which the story takes place only very few cars (that were called automobiles back then) were seen on the so-called roads in the Southern U.S. and a journey this long represents a considerable chal</span>
  <span id="freeText16249680063117388504" style="display:none">I had some trouble to fight my way through this novel.<br><br>The story is actually quite interesting and amusing: The three heroes, 11 yo Lucius, Boon Hogganbeck and "Uncle" Ned pilfer the car of Lucius' grandfather and want to travel for four days to the "big city". You have to understand that at the time in which the story takes place only very few cars (that were called automobiles back then) were seen on the so-called roads in the Southern U.S. and a journey this long represents a considerable challenge to man and machine.<br><br>It is the description of this journey from Jefferson, MS to Memphis, TN, which I liked best about the book. The rest is somehow plowed under the too complicated structured monsters of sentences. I generally have no problem with long sentences, as long as they come along harmonically/melodically and do not disturb my flow of reading. Here it was often not the case. <br><br>THE REIVERS is the last novel by William Faulkner and also the first one I've read. After reading I'm not sure if I want to deal with more of Faulkner's works in the near future. After all I'm reading novels mostly for fun and entertainment.<br><br>Rating 2½ of 5 stars.<br><br><a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img alt="Creative Commons License" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1380148217i/680962.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
