<div id="review_1367362927" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1367362927" />
    <a title="Jim Peterson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24498353-jim-peterson"><img alt="Jim Peterson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1381082195p2/24498353.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1367362927?book_show_action=true">Aug 18, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jim Peterson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jim Peterson" href="/user/show/24498353-jim-peterson">Jim Peterson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24498353-jim-peterson?shelf=english">english</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24498353-jim-peterson?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24498353-jim-peterson?shelf=pulitzer">pulitzer</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24498353-jim-peterson?shelf=nobel-prize-winners">nobel-prize-winners</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1367362927" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11569165321180543102">If you don’t want to bother with my ramblings, just skip to the last paragraph for my opinion of the book :-)<br/><br/>I live in Europe, and several times in the past when someone discovered I was (and still am) an American, they might go on to talk about some American author and what did I think about him or her. I would either admit I hadn’t read the author in question or pretend as if I had – both of which options would be rather awkward. And so, I’ve decided to remedy that situation and have been spen</span>
  <span id="freeText11569165321180543102" style="display:none">If you don’t want to bother with my ramblings, just skip to the last paragraph for my opinion of the book :-)<br /><br />I live in Europe, and several times in the past when someone discovered I was (and still am) an American, they might go on to talk about some American author and what did I think about him or her. I would either admit I hadn’t read the author in question or pretend as if I had – both of which options would be rather awkward. And so, I’ve decided to remedy that situation and have been spending most of my reading time trying to catch up on American authors. Hence Faulkner. <br /><br />Faulkner is not easy to read – at first, at least. He writes extremely long sentences, many of which would be marked with red ink by English teachers as “run-on sentences”. Reading Faulkner felt like my first attempts at reading German. You read, re-read, push on, not really understanding everything, but knowing that soon the blurry picture in your head will come more and more into focus. <br /><br />I read up on Faulkner’s style: stream of consciousness. Ah hah. And IF that’s what it is (a stream), then what the h— was I doing re-reading anything? Why not just go with the flow? And that’s what I did. I just read it quickly, not worrying about the details, and soon everything became clear – and I started loving it. Really, really loving it.<br /><br />The Reivers is a fantastic story, the writing is like nothing I’ve ever seen (probably it wouldn’t get past the editors today) and the story transported me to the old south. I have already bought three more of Faulkner’s books, but I think I’m going to read something short and simple first…<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11569165321180543102" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


