    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_563911079" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/563911079" />
    <a title="Justin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1278726-justin"><img alt="Justin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1360898899p2/1278726.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/563911079?book_show_action=true">Mar 17, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Justin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Justin" href="/user/show/1278726-justin">Justin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer563911079" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13174226878402783371">This was my fourth and final Faulkner novel for the month of March. I have to admit that I have a bit of Faulkner fatigue which in all transparency could have impacted my rating. This is Faulkner&apos;s most accessible novel - a Huck Finn style coming of age story that is fun, exciting, and subtle in its commentary on race and manhood. It has almost no resemblance to anything else he has written. It&apos;s really quite a tribute to Faulkner&apos;s ability that he can write across such diverse genre&apos;s while sti</span>
  <span id="freeText13174226878402783371" style="display:none">This was my fourth and final Faulkner novel for the month of March. I have to admit that I have a bit of Faulkner fatigue which in all transparency could have impacted my rating. This is Faulkner's most accessible novel - a Huck Finn style coming of age story that is fun, exciting, and subtle in its commentary on race and manhood. It has almost no resemblance to anything else he has written. It's really quite a tribute to Faulkner's ability that he can write across such diverse genre's while still maintaining a core set of truths that he sets out to convey.<br /><br />I won't go into the details of the story which are available in the Good Reads overview. Suffice to say it was enjoyable and I was particularly impressed with Faulkner's treatment of race - which was significantly more subtle than in past novels - particularly the noble characters of Ned and Uncle Parshum. However, overall, I was less impressed with this than other Faulkner novels - not because it was more accessible, but rather because I just never really connected with it in the same way that I did with Absalom, Absalom! The fact that this won the Pulitzer Prize probably says something about critics ability to understand greatness at the time that it arises (rather than as a lifetime achievement award at the end).</span>
  <a data-text-id="13174226878402783371" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


